    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Parts Catalog Overview",
            Slug = "parts-overview",
            Summary = "What parts are, the three classification axes (procurement, inventory class, item kind), statuses, BOMs, vendor sources, routing, and how parts connect to jobs, inventory, purchasing, and sales.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/parts"]""",
            Tags = """["parts","bom","operations","inventory","catalog","sourcing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Parts Catalog Overview\n\nThe Parts Catalog is your central register for every item your shop makes, buys, or stocks. Each part record holds the full picture — what the part is, how you get it, where it lives in inventory, and how it's built. Parts tie into nearly everything else: jobs use them, inventory counts them, purchase orders buy them, sales orders sell them, and operations describe how to make them.\n\n### What Is a Part?\n\nA part is any item your business tracks — finished goods, raw materials, sub-assemblies, components, consumables, fasteners, electronics, packaging, and tooling. Every part gets a part number and a name. New parts start as Draft and move through Prototype, Active, and eventually Obsolete.\n\n### The Three Classification Choices\n\nInstead of picking one \"type\", you describe a part along three independent choices on the New Part screen:\n\n1. **How you get it (Procurement Source).**\n   - **Make** — you build it in-house. You can still send out single steps to a vendor.\n   - **Buy** — you purchase it complete from a vendor.\n   - **Subcontract** — a vendor builds the whole part; you never touch it.\n   - **Phantom** — a stand-in assembly that never physically exists; planning looks straight through it to its child parts.\n2. **Which inventory bucket it lives in** — raw material, component, sub-assembly, finished good, consumable, or tool.\n3. **Item kind** — a descriptive tag your admin sets up, such as fastener, electronic, packaging, hardware, or material.\n\nNot every mix makes sense — there's a set of eleven that do. Your choices decide which tabs show up, which guided flow you get when you create the part, and which checks run before it can go Active. The detail page adjusts its tabs to match automatically.\n\n**These first two choices lock once the part exists.** How you get the part and which inventory bucket it's in shape everything downstream — the tabs you see, the checks that run, the way cost is figured. Changing them later would break the part's history, so if a part truly needs reclassifying, use the dedicated migration tool.\n\n### Core Identity Fields\n\nBeyond those three choices, every part carries:\n\n- **Traceability** — track nothing (bulk), by batch (lot), or one-by-one (serial).\n- **ABC class** — A, B, or C, to prioritize by value (how often you count it, how tightly you control it).\n- **Manufacturer** and **manufacturer part number** — the original maker's identity, separate from a distributor's own number.\n- **Revision** — the engineering revision letter. Starts at A.\n- **Description** — longer notes.\n\n### The Status Lifecycle\n\nFour statuses control what a part can do:\n\n- **Draft** — the record exists but isn't finished; hidden from production and purchasing.\n- **Prototype** — usable in jobs and inventory, but flagged as not final.\n- **Active** — fully approved for production, purchasing, and sales. Where most parts settle once ready.\n- **Obsolete** — kept for history. Won't show up on new orders.\n\nParts are never truly deleted. Most status changes happen right on the Identity tab — but the most important one, moving a part from Draft to Active, has its own button that checks the part is ready first (see below).\n\n### Promoting a Draft Part to Active\n\nA new part starts as **Draft**, meaning the record exists but isn't finished — it stays out of production and purchasing. To make it usable everywhere, promote it to **Active**. The system checks that the part is actually ready first.\n\nThere are two ways to get to Active, and both run the same readiness checks:\n\n1. **Finish the New Part flow.** Click Complete on the last step. If everything passes, the part goes Active on its own and you return to the parts list. If something's missing, you get a message naming exactly what to fix (for example, \"Finish Routing before moving on\"), and the flow stays open so you can.\n2. **Use the Promote to Active button.** Open a Draft part and go to the Identity tab — the button sits below the barcode. Click it, and the system runs the same checks. If it passes, the part goes Active. If not, a panel lists exactly what's missing — add the missing piece (a component, a cost, a stocking unit, and so on) and click Promote again.\n\n**The readiness checks** are what must be in place before a part can go Active. Which ones apply depends on how you get the part and which bucket it's in. The common ones:\n\n- **Basics** — a name plus your two main choices. Always met once the part exists.\n- **Components** — at least one line in the bill of materials. Needed for assemblies; skipped for single-piece and simple bought parts.\n- **Routing** — at least one manufacturing step. Needed for parts you make; skipped for bought, subcontracted, and phantom parts.\n- **Cost** — a manual cost or a calculated one. Needed for most stocked parts; skipped for tools and phantoms.\n- **Sourcing** — a preferred vendor picked. Needed for bought and subcontracted parts; optional otherwise.\n- **Stocking unit** — a unit the part is stored in. Needed for everything except phantoms, and usually filled in for you.\n\nMoving a part to Obsolete or Prototype has no checks — set it right on the Identity tab. Only Draft to Active is gated. Prototype is for parts you want usable while still marked as not final.\n\n### The Detail Page\n\nThe part detail page organizes its tabs to fit the part — the tabs you see depend on how you get it and which bucket it's in. Common tabs:\n\n- **Identity** — always first. Part number, your two locked choices, name, revision, description, and status. Edit the name, description, revision, and status right here.\n- **Inventory** — minimum stock, reorder point, reorder quantity, safety stock, traceability, and ABC class. Hidden for parts you don't stock.\n- **MRP** — planning settings: how orders are sized, order quantities and multiples, and planning windows. Hidden when the part isn't MRP-planned.\n- **Cost** — a manual cost, the current calculated cost, valuation class, and a landed-cost breakdown. Hidden for phantoms.\n- **Pricing** — list prices, effective dates, and history.\n- **Material** — material spec plus weight, dimensions, and volume, entered in whatever unit you prefer.\n- **Units** — the units the part is stocked, bought, and sold in.\n- **Quality** — whether to inspect on receipt, and which checklist, how often, and when to skip.\n- **Routing** — the manufacturing steps.\n- **Components** — the bill of materials, as a table or a tree.\n- **Sources** — the vendors that supply this part, one row each.\n- **Alternates** — substitute parts.\n- **Purchase History** — recent purchase orders that included this part.\n- **3D Viewer** — shows up only when a 3D model is attached.\n- **Activity** — a running log of every change to the part's definition.\n- **Files** — always last. Drawings, models, and datasheets.\n\nEach tab you can edit has its own Save and Cancel in its lower-right corner. Editing Identity won't touch Inventory — each save covers only its own tab. There's no single page-wide Save.\n\n### Vendor Sources (Sources Tab)\n\nFor parts you buy — or bought options on a part you make — the **Sources** tab lists each vendor that supplies the part, one row per vendor. Each row holds that vendor's own sourcing details:\n\n- The vendor's part number\n- The vendor's manufacturer part number, when they're reselling someone else's part\n- That vendor's lead time, minimum order, and pack size\n- Country of origin and tariff (HTS) code\n- Whether they're on your approved list, their certifications, and when they last quoted\n- A **preferred** marker — one preferred vendor per part at most\n- **Quantity-break pricing** — cheaper rates at higher quantities, each with start and end dates\n\nAdding a source works like any other new record, and you manage its price breaks right in place. Marking a new vendor preferred clears the marker off the old one.\n\n### Bill of Materials (Components)\n\nFor parts you make (and phantoms), the Components tab lists everything that goes into the part:\n\n- **Child part** — searched from the catalog, and never the part itself.\n- **Quantity** — how many per finished unit.\n- **Source** — whether the component is made in-house (which can spin up a sub-job), bought, or pulled from stock.\n- **Reference designator** — an engineering reference like R1, C4, or J2.\n- **Lead time** — how long that component takes to get.\n- **Notes** — anything else worth recording.\n\nYou can view components as a flat, sortable table or as a tree. A reverse view shows which parent assemblies use this part.\n\n**Revision history.** The Components tab also keeps a read-only history. Each time you change the component list — add, edit, or remove a line — the system freezes a new version and stamps its effective date. The history lists those versions newest-first, flags the current one, and shows how many lines each had. Open any version to see exactly what the part was made of at that moment. You don't create versions by hand; editing the list does it for you. This is the record of \"what was this assembly made of, and when did it change?\" — key for traceability and for understanding why an older job's cost or materials differ from today's.\n\n### Routing (Operations)\n\nParts you make have a Routing tab that lists the manufacturing steps in order. Each step can have a title, work instructions, a work center, an estimated time, and a quality checkpoint with pass criteria, and can reference another step it depends on. Any single step can be sent out to a vendor — different from sending out the whole part. You can also tell each step which components it consumes. Steps support their own file attachments and activity log. View the routing as a list of cards or as a flow diagram.\n\n### How Parts Connect to Other Modules\n\n**Jobs** — a job on the board can be linked to a part. The part's components drive what materials are needed, and its routing defines the production steps.\n\n**Inventory** — parts are tracked in storage locations and bins. The Inventory tab shows total quantity on hand and warns you when stock drops below the minimum.\n\n**Purchase Orders** — when a component is marked as bought, the system knows it needs purchasing, and the preferred vendor drives the order.\n\n**Sales Orders and Quotes** — parts show up as line items, priced from the part's price history or a vendor's quantity-break rate.\n\n**Assets** — tool parts can be linked to a tooling asset to track shot count and maintenance.\n\n**Barcodes** — every part can have a barcode label printed. Scanning it on the Parts page drops the value into search and finds the part instantly.\n\n### Creating a Part\n\nNew Part opens with four quick questions: how you get the part, which bucket it's in, an optional item-kind tag, and whether you want the quick single-page form or the guided step-by-step flow (it recommends one). From your answers, the system picks the right flow and walks you through the fields that matter — basics, inventory, quality, sourcing, costing, and so on. You can stop at any step; your progress is saved as a draft and shown as a faint row on the parts list, ready to pick back up.\n\nSimple cases like raw materials and consumables skip straight to the one-page quick form.\n\n### View Modes\n\nThe parts list has two views: a sortable table with column controls, and a grid of visual cards. Switch in the upper-right; your choice is remembered.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Parts Catalog — Guided Tour",
