            Summary = "A guided tour of the parts list, axis filters, view toggle, the New Part fork, and a glance at the resolver-driven detail page (Identity / Inventory / Cost / Sources / BOM / Routing / Activity / Files).",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 2,
            AppRoutes = """["/parts"]""",
            Tags = """["parts","bom","operations","walkthrough","sourcing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/parts","startButtonLabel":"Tour Parts Catalog","steps":[{"element":"[data-testid='new-part-btn']","popover":{"title":"New Part","description":"Click here to start a new part. You'll answer four quick questions first: how you get the part, which inventory bucket it's in, an optional item-kind tag, and whether you want the quick form or the guided flow. From your answers, the system picks the right flow and walks you through the fields that matter.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".filters-bar app-input","popover":{"title":"Search Parts","description":"Search by part number, name, manufacturer, or an outside part number. Press Enter to apply. Barcode scanners feed straight into this box — scan a label and the matching part pops up.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".filters-bar app-select:nth-of-type(1)","popover":{"title":"Filter by Status","description":"Narrow the list by status: Draft (still being set up), Prototype (in testing), Active (approved for use), or Obsolete (kept for history but off new orders). Pick 'All' to see everything.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".filters-bar app-select:nth-of-type(2)","popover":{"title":"Filter by How You Get It","description":"Narrow by how the part is sourced: made in-house, bought, subcontracted (a vendor builds it whole), or phantom (a stand-in assembly that never physically exists). Combine with the bucket filter to zero in.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".filters-bar app-select:nth-of-type(3)","popover":{"title":"Filter by Inventory Bucket","description":"Narrow by bucket: raw material, component, sub-assembly, finished good, consumable, or tool. This choice decides which stocking, traceability, and ABC rules apply to the part.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".view-toggle","popover":{"title":"Switch Views","description":"Flip between a sortable table with column controls and a grid of visual cards. Your choice is remembered next time.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"The Parts List","description":"Click any row to open a part. Columns show the part number, name, how you get it, its bucket, status, component count, current price, and how complete the record is. Click a heading to sort, and use the gear to show, hide, or reorder columns. Half-finished drafts appear as faint rows pinned to the top — click one to pick up where you left off, or click the X to discard it.","side":"top"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Field Reference (QuickRef) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Parts Catalog Field Reference",
            Slug = "parts-field-reference",
            Summary = "Complete reference for every field, axis, status, validation rule, table column, and detail-page cluster in the Parts Catalog.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 3,
            AppRoutes = """["/parts"]""",
            Tags = """["parts","bom","operations","reference","sourcing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"Parts Catalog Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"The Three Classification Choices (set on the New Part screen)","items":[{"label":"How you get it (required)","value":"Made in-house, bought, subcontracted, or phantom. Sets which guided flow you get, which tabs show up, and which checks run before the part can go Active. Locked once the part exists."},{"label":"Inventory bucket (required)","value":"Raw material, component, sub-assembly, finished good, consumable, or tool. Decides which stocking, traceability, and ABC rules apply. Locked once the part exists."},{"label":"Item kind (optional)","value":"A descriptive tag your admin sets up, such as fastener, electronic, packaging, hardware, or material. Purely descriptive — it doesn't drive any behavior."}]},{"heading":"Identity Fields","items":[{"label":"Part Number","value":"Created for you and can't be changed. It uses a short prefix for the part's category plus a running number."},{"label":"Name (required)","value":"A short, clear name for the part (for example, 'Sheath Mudkipper'). Up to 256 characters."},{"label":"Description","value":"Longer notes. Optional, up to 2000 characters."},{"label":"Revision","value":"The engineering revision letter. Starts at A; bump it (A, B, C) when the design changes. Up to 5 characters."},{"label":"Status (required)","value":"Draft, Prototype, Active, or Obsolete. Change it right on the Identity tab."}]},{"heading":"Core Identity Fields","items":[{"label":"Traceability","value":"Track nothing (bulk), by batch (lot), or one-by-one (serial). Required."},{"label":"ABC Class","value":"A (high value, tight control), B (moderate), C (low value, loose control), or unset. Sets how often you count it and how tightly you control it."},{"label":"Manufacturer","value":"The original maker's company name. Optional, and separate from a distributor's name."},{"label":"Manufacturer Part Number","value":"The original maker's part number. Optional, and separate from a distributor's own number — a part can carry both."}]},{"heading":"Inventory Fields","items":[{"label":"Min Stock","value":"The least you want on hand. Drop below it and you get a low-stock warning. Optional; can't be negative."},{"label":"Reorder Point","value":"The level at which the part should be reordered. Used by planning. Optional; can't be negative."},{"label":"Reorder Quantity","value":"How many to order when it's time to reorder. Optional."},{"label":"Safety Stock (days)","value":"Extra days of buffer stock to keep beyond the reorder point. Optional."},{"label":"Traceability","value":"Track nothing, by batch, or one-by-one. See Core Identity Fields."},{"label":"ABC Class","value":"A, B, C, or unset. See Core Identity Fields."}]},{"heading":"Cost Fields","items":[{"label":"Manual Cost","value":"A price you type in yourself. When set, it overrides the calculated cost. Clear it to go back to the calculated value."},{"label":"Calculated Cost","value":"The current cost the system works out for you. It refreshes on its own whenever components, vendors, or prices change."},{"label":"Valuation Class","value":"A grouping used for inventory valuation. Your admin configures the options."},{"label":"Landed Cost Breakdown","value":"Shows the unit cost plus freight, duty, and tariffs, pulled from vendor pricing and shipment costs."}]},{"heading":"Promote to Active & Readiness Checks","items":[{"label":"Promote to Active (button)","value":"On the Identity tab of a Draft part, below the barcode. Only shows for Draft parts. Runs the readiness checks and, if they pass, moves the part to Active."},{"label":"What the button tells you","value":"It runs the readiness checks and, if anything blocks the move, tells you exactly what's missing. Promotion never fails silently — you always learn why."},{"label":"Missing-info panel","value":"If a check fails, a panel lists what's still missing. Fix each item and click Promote again. Close it with the X."},{"label":"Finishing the flow (the other way)","value":"Clicking Complete on the last step of the New Part flow runs the same checks and moves the part to Active when they pass. If it's blocked, the message names the step to finish first."},{"label":"Check: Basics","value":"A name plus your two main choices. Always met once the part exists, since you pick those choices before creating it."},{"label":"Check: Components","value":"At least one line in the bill of materials. Needed for assemblies. Message: 'BOM not yet defined.'"},{"label":"Check: Routing","value":"At least one manufacturing step. Needed for parts you make. Message: 'Routing operations not yet defined.'"},{"label":"Check: Cost","value":"A manual or calculated cost. Needed for most stocked parts; skipped for tools and phantoms. Message: 'Cost not yet set.'"},{"label":"Check: Sourcing","value":"A preferred vendor picked. Needed for bought and subcontracted parts; optional for others. Message: 'Preferred vendor not yet selected.'"},{"label":"Check: Stocking unit","value":"A unit the part is stored in. Needed for everything except phantoms, and usually filled in for you. Message: 'Stock unit of measure not yet set.'"},{"label":"Which checks apply","value":"Depends on how you get the part and which bucket it's in — each guided flow decides which steps, and so which checks, are required. A bought consumable has far fewer checks than a made finished good."},{"label":"Moving to Obsolete or Prototype","value":"Set it right on the Identity tab — no checks. Only Draft to Active is gated."}]},{"heading":"Sources Tab (Vendors That Supply the Part)","items":[{"label":"Add Vendor Source","value":"Opens a panel to add a vendor for this part. You must pick a vendor."},{"label":"Vendor Part Number","value":"The vendor's own catalog number for this part."},{"label":"Vendor Manufacturer Part Number","value":"The maker's part number as the vendor lists it — useful when the vendor is a distributor reselling someone else's part."},{"label":"Lead Time (days)","value":"How long this vendor takes to supply the part. Overrides the part's default for this vendor."},{"label":"Minimum Order","value":"The smallest quantity this vendor will sell."},{"label":"Pack Size","value":"This vendor ships in multiples of this number."},{"label":"Country of Origin","value":"Where the part is made, for customs purposes."},{"label":"Tariff (HTS) Code","value":"The harmonized tariff code, used to figure import duties."},{"label":"On Approved List","value":"An on/off marker for whether this vendor is on your approved list."},{"label":"Certifications","value":"Quality certifications, such as ISO 9001, AS9100, or RoHS. Free text."},{"label":"Last Quoted","value":"When the vendor last quoted this part, so you can spot stale sources."},{"label":"Preferred","value":"An on/off marker. One preferred vendor per part at most — turning it on for one vendor turns it off for the others."},{"label":"Price Breaks","value":"Cheaper rates at higher quantities — each with a minimum quantity, a price, and start and end dates. Add, edit, or remove them right here."}]},{"heading":"Components (Bill of Materials)","items":[{"label":"Child Part (required)","value":"Searched from the catalog, and never the part itself."},{"label":"Quantity (required)","value":"How many of this component per finished unit. Must be more than zero. Defaults to 1."},{"label":"Source","value":"Made in-house (which can spin up a sub-job), bought, or pulled from stock. Defaults to bought."},{"label":"Reference Designator","value":"An engineering reference like R1, C4, or J2."},{"label":"Lead Time","value":"How long this component takes to get, shown as a number of days."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Anything else worth recording."}]},{"heading":"Alternates Tab (Substitute Parts)","items":[{"label":"Add Alternate (button)","value":"Opens a panel to add a substitute. You can even create a brand-new part right there if it isn't in the catalog yet."},{"label":"Alternate Part (required)","value":"Searched from the catalog. The part this one can be swapped with."},{"label":"Type","value":"Substitute, equivalent, or superseded — describing how the two parts relate. Each shows as a colored label."},{"label":"Priority (required)","value":"A whole number, 1 or higher. Lower means preferred, so the system suggests it first."},{"label":"Conversion Factor","value":"Optional. The ratio when the swap isn't one-for-one (for example, 1.2 means you need 1.2 of the alternate per 1 of the original)."},{"label":"Approved","value":"An on/off marker for whether the substitute is cleared for production. Unapproved rows show an Approve button you can click right in the table."},{"label":"Both Directions","value":"On means the swap works both ways (each part is an alternate of the other); off means one-way only. The table shows an arrow to indicate direction. Defaults to on."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Anything else worth recording."},{"label":"Approve (in the table)","value":"An Approve button on an unapproved substitute — click it to approve without reopening the panel."},{"label":"Remove (in the table)","value":"A trash icon that asks you to confirm, then removes the substitute link."}]},{"heading":"Serials Tab (Parts Tracked One-by-One)","items":[{"label":"When it appears","value":"Only when the part is tracked one-by-one (serial). Bulk and batch-tracked parts don't have this tab."},{"label":"New Serial (button)","value":"Opens a panel to create a serial number."},{"label":"Serial Number (required)","value":"The unique serial value. Up to 100 characters."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Optional."},{"label":"Status filter","value":"Narrow the list by status: all, available, in use, shipped, returned, scrapped, or quarantined."},{"label":"List columns","value":"Shows each serial's number, status, location, job, manufactured date, and how many child serials it has."},{"label":"Open a serial","value":"Click a row to see its details: part, job, current location, customer, parent serial, manufactured and shipped dates, and notes."},{"label":"History (in the detail)","value":"A time-ordered log of that serial's moves and lifecycle — the action, where it moved from and to, and when."},{"label":"Genealogy (in the detail)","value":"Opens a tree showing this serial's parent and child serials — which serialized sub-assemblies were built into this unit, traced down through the build."},{"label":"Status values","value":"Available, in use, shipped, returned, scrapped, or quarantined — each shown as a colored label."}]},{"heading":"Component Revision History (read-only)","items":[{"label":"What it is","value":"A read-only panel on the Components tab that lists every saved version of the component list, newest first."},{"label":"How versions are created","value":"On their own — every time you add, edit, or remove a component, the system freezes a new version. You never create one by hand."},{"label":"What each row shows","value":"The version number, a 'current' mark on the active one, the effective date, how many lines it had, and any notes."},{"label":"Open a version","value":"Click a row to see its frozen snapshot: each line's part number, description, quantity and unit, source, reference designator, and notes."},{"label":"Why it's there","value":"It answers 'what was this assembly made of, and when did it change?' — explaining why an older job's materials or cost differ from today's."}]},{"heading":"Routing (Parts You Make)","items":[{"label":"Step Number","value":"The order of the step (1, 2, 3...). Filled in with the next number for you."},{"label":"Title (required)","value":"A short name for the step, such as 'CNC Rough Cut', 'Deburr', or 'Heat Treat'. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"Instructions","value":"Detailed work instructions for the operator."},{"label":"Work Center","value":"The work center that runs the step. Optional."},{"label":"Estimated Minutes","value":"How long the step should take. Optional; at least 1 if you set it."},{"label":"Send Out This Step","value":"Turn on to send just this one step to a vendor. Different from subcontracting the whole part."},{"label":"Quality Checkpoint","value":"Turn on to require an inspection before the next step can start."},{"label":"Quality Criteria","value":"What the inspection checks for. Shown when the quality checkpoint is on."},{"label":"Step Materials","value":"The components consumed at this step, each with the quantity used here."}]},{"heading":"Quality","items":[{"label":"Inspect on Receipt","value":"Turn on to inspect this part every time it's received."},{"label":"Inspection Checklist","value":"Which checklist the inspection uses."},{"label":"Inspection Frequency","value":"Inspect every time, a sample, or skip after a run of passes."},{"label":"Skip After","value":"After this many passing inspections in a row, later receipts skip inspection until a defect turns up."}]},{"heading":"Material","items":[{"label":"Material Spec","value":"The material the part is made of, such as 6061-T6 aluminum, 304 stainless, or ABS plastic."},{"label":"Weight","value":"The part's weight. Type it in whatever unit you like (g, kg, oz, lb) and it keeps your unit exactly."},{"label":"Length, Width, Height","value":"The part's dimensions. Type them in mm, cm, m, in, or ft and it keeps your unit exactly."},{"label":"Volume","value":"The part's volume. Type it in mL, L, oz, or gal and it keeps your unit exactly."},{"label":"Valuation Class","value":"A grouping used for inventory valuation."}]},{"heading":"Units","items":[{"label":"Stock Unit","value":"The unit the part is stored in — the main inventory unit."},{"label":"Purchase Unit","value":"The unit the part is bought in. May differ from the stock unit (for example, stock by piece, buy by case)."},{"label":"Sales Unit","value":"The unit the part is sold in."}]},{"heading":"MRP (Planning)","items":[{"label":"Include in Planning","value":"Whether planning includes this part in its runs."},{"label":"Order-Sizing Rule","value":"How planning groups demand into orders — fixed quantity, lot-for-lot, economic order quantity, or fixed period."},{"label":"Fixed Order Quantity","value":"For the fixed-quantity rule. Always order this much."},{"label":"Minimum Order Quantity","value":"The smallest any single order can be."},{"label":"Order Multiple","value":"Order in multiples of this number."},{"label":"Planning Window (days)","value":"Inside this window, planning won't create new orders on its own — you control them by hand."},{"label":"Demand Window (days)","value":"Inside this window, demand changes aren't allowed without an override."}]},{"heading":"Pricing","items":[{"label":"Set New Price","value":"Enter a price and save to create a new price, marking the previous one as history."},{"label":"Effective From","value":"When the new price starts. Defaults to today."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Optional. Why the price changed."},{"label":"Price History","value":"Past prices, each with its start and end dates (or '---' for the current one)."}]},{"heading":"Detail Page Tabs","items":[{"label":"Tabs fit the part","value":"The tabs aren't fixed — they're chosen from how you get the part and which bucket it's in. Identity is always first and Files always last. Activity sits as a footer below the tab, not as its own tab."},{"label":"Common tabs","value":"Identity, Inventory, MRP, Cost, Pricing, Material, Units, Quality, Routing, Components, Sources, Alternates, Purchase History, 3D Viewer, Activity, and Files."},{"label":"Shareable links","value":"The tab you're on is kept in the web address, so refreshing or sharing a link lands on the right tab."},{"label":"Per-tab save","value":"Each editable tab has its own Save and Cancel in its lower-right corner. There's no page-wide Save — editing Identity won't affect Inventory."}]},{"heading":"Parts List Columns","items":[{"label":"Part #","value":"The part number, created for you. Sortable."},{"label":"Name","value":"The part's name, with a badge showing how complete the record is. Sortable."},{"label":"How You Get It","value":"Made, bought, subcontracted, or phantom, shown as a label. Sortable."},{"label":"Bucket","value":"Raw material, component, sub-assembly, finished good, consumable, or tool, shown as a label. Sortable."},{"label":"Status","value":"A colored label: Active is green, Draft gray, Prototype blue, Obsolete red. Sortable and filterable."},{"label":"Component Count","value":"How many components the part has directly."},{"label":"Current Price","value":"The current list price, or '---' if none is set."},{"label":"Completeness","value":"A label showing how complete the record is, across identity, sourcing, pricing, and quality."}]},{"heading":"Validation Rules","items":[{"label":"How you get it / Inventory bucket","value":"Required when you create the part, and can't be changed afterward."},{"label":"Name","value":"Required. Up to 256 characters."},{"label":"Description","value":"Optional. Up to 2000 characters."},{"label":"Revision","value":"Optional. Up to 5 characters. Defaults to 'A'."},{"label":"Traceability","value":"Required. Track nothing, by batch, or one-by-one."},{"label":"Min Stock / Reorder Point / Safety Stock","value":"Optional. Can't be negative."},{"label":"Component Quantity","value":"Required. Must be more than zero."},{"label":"Step Number","value":"Required. At least 1."},{"label":"Step Title","value":"Required. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"One preferred vendor per part","value":"The system allows at most one preferred vendor per part — marking one preferred clears the marker off the rest."},{"label":"Save button and its warnings","value":"When a form isn't valid, Save is disabled and a small warning triangle appears next to it. Click the triangle to see what needs fixing."}]},{"heading":"Buttons and Actions","items":[{"label":"New Part (page header)","value":"Opens the four-question New Part screen."},{"label":"Resume Draft (parts list)","value":"Click a faint draft row (a half-finished part) to pick up where you left off."},{"label":"Discard Draft","value":"The X on a faint draft row. Throws away the half-finished part."},{"label":"Edit (tab header)","value":"Each editable tab has an Edit button. Click it to edit just that tab."},{"label":"Save / Cancel (tab footer)","value":"Per tab. Save commits that tab's changes; Cancel drops your edits and leaves edit mode."},{"label":"Status change","value":"The status picker on the Identity tab — Draft, Prototype, Active, or Obsolete. Use it for Prototype and Obsolete. Draft to Active goes through the Promote to Active button instead."},{"label":"Promote to Active (Identity tab, Draft only)","value":"Runs the readiness checks and moves Draft to Active when they pass, or lists what's missing."},{"label":"Add Alternate (Alternates tab)","value":"Opens the panel to add a substitute part."},{"label":"Approve Alternate (in the table)","value":"An Approve button on an unapproved substitute row."},{"label":"New Serial (Serials tab)","value":"Opens the panel to create a serial number (only for parts tracked one-by-one)."},{"label":"View Genealogy (serial detail)","value":"Opens the parent-and-child serial tree for the selected serial."},{"label":"Add Vendor Source (Sources tab)","value":"Opens the panel to add a vendor for this part."},{"label":"Add Price Break","value":"On a vendor source — adds a cheaper rate for a higher quantity."},{"label":"Add Component","value":"Opens the panel to add a component, with a search for the child part."},{"label":"Add Step","value":"Opens the panel to add a manufacturing step, with the next step number filled in."},{"label":"Switch Views (page level)","value":"Flip between the table and the card grid."},{"label":"Open a part (parts list)","value":"Click a row to open the part."}]},{"heading":"What Gets Logged","items":[{"label":"Created","value":"When a part is created, one activity entry is logged, naming its number, name, how you get it, and its bucket."},{"label":"Updated","value":"On each save, one entry is logged summarizing all the fields you changed."},{"label":"Deleted","value":"When a part is deleted, one 'deleted' entry is logged. The part itself is kept, just hidden."},{"label":"Vendor changes","value":"Adding, changing, or removing a vendor source — or a price break — logs an entry on both the part and the vendor."}]},{"heading":"Barcode Scanning","items":[{"label":"On the Parts page","value":"While you're on the Parts page, scans feed into the search box."},{"label":"What a scan does","value":"The scanned value drops into search and the list reloads to find the part by its barcode number."},{"label":"Supported scanners","value":"USB barcode scanners and NFC tag readers, set to act like a keyboard."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Knowledge Check (Quiz) ───────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Parts Catalog Knowledge Check",
            Slug = "parts-quiz",
            Summary = "Test your knowledge: the three classification axes, identity immutability, BOM source types, vendor sources, routing, traceability, and the per-cluster save model.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/parts"]""",
            Tags = """["parts","bom","operations","quiz","sourcing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"pt1","text":"A part is built from several sub-components in your shop. Which combination of how-you-get-it and inventory bucket fits?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Bought / Component"},{"id":"b","text":"Made / Sub-assembly","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Subcontracted / Finished good"},{"id":"d","text":"Phantom / Raw material"}],"explanation":"Made because you build it in-house, and sub-assembly because it's an assembly that itself goes into something larger. You'll get a Components tab, and a Routing tab because parts you make have manufacturing steps."},{"id":"pt2","text":"What's the difference between subcontracting a whole part and sending out a single manufacturing step?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They mean the same thing — both send work to a vendor"},{"id":"b","text":"A subcontracted part is built entirely by a vendor; sending out a step means one step goes to a vendor while you make the rest in-house","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Subcontracting a whole part is no longer supported; only single steps can be sent out now"},{"id":"d","text":"Sending out a step creates a purchase order automatically; subcontracting a part doesn't"}],"explanation":"These are two different scopes. A subcontracted part is fully outsourced — the vendor delivers it complete. Sending out a single step on a part you make means just that one step goes out (for example, you machine the housing in-house but send it out for anodizing)."},{"id":"pt3","text":"Why are 'how you get it' and the inventory bucket locked once a part is created?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They aren't — there's an Edit button on the Identity tab that lets you change them"},{"id":"b","text":"They drive which tabs appear, which checks run, which flow you get when creating the part, and what runs before it goes Active. Changing them later would break every downstream reference and the part's history","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It's a technical limitation with no business reason"},{"id":"d","text":"Only 'how you get it' is locked; the bucket can be changed freely"}],"explanation":"Both choices are baked into every cost calculation, every assembly that uses this part, every vendor source, and the part's own history. Reclassifying later would quietly break all of it. If a part truly needs reclassifying, use the dedicated migration tool that redoes the setup and records the change — not an inline edit."},{"id":"pt4","text":"What does tracking a part by batch (lot) mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The part is tracked by individual serial numbers, one per unit"},{"id":"b","text":"The part is tracked by batch — receipts, moves, and use are recorded against the batch, not against individual units","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part can only be sold by the batch, never split"},{"id":"d","text":"The part is exempt from inventory tracking entirely"}],"explanation":"Tracking by batch means the smallest thing you track is the batch. Use it for materials and chemicals where you can't tell individual units apart. Track one-by-one (serial) for high-value or regulated items where every unit needs its own identity, and track nothing for bulk consumables where neither matters."},{"id":"pt5","text":"You're editing a part. You change the name on the Identity tab and click Save. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The whole part is saved — Identity, Inventory, Cost, and every other tab"},{"id":"b","text":"Only the Identity tab's fields are saved. Other tabs aren't touched","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Nothing — there's no per-tab save; the page has one global Save button"},{"id":"d","text":"The save fails because the Inventory tab has unsaved edits too"}],"explanation":"Each editable tab has its own Save and Cancel in the lower-right corner, and each Save covers only that tab's fields. So you can edit Identity safely without touching Inventory — no risk of accidentally saving stale values from another tab."},{"id":"pt6","text":"You add a vendor source and turn on 'Preferred'. Another vendor on the same part was already preferred. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The save is rejected — you must turn off the other preferred vendor first"},{"id":"b","text":"Both vendors end up preferred — the rule is only a suggestion","isCorrect":false},{"id":"c","text":"The old preferred vendor is turned off automatically — a part can have at most one preferred vendor, and the part's preferred-vendor pointer updates to the new one","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing catches it until the next time you view the part"}],"explanation":"A part can have at most one preferred vendor, and the system keeps it that way: turning on preferred for one vendor turns it off for the others in the same save. The part also keeps a pointer to its preferred vendor for quick reference, and that updates at the same time."},{"id":"pt7","text":"A vendor has a price break for 100 or more at $1.50, and a base rate for 10 or more at $2.00. A buyer asks for 250 units. Which rate applies?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"$2.00 because that rate was added first"},{"id":"b","text":"$1.50 because 250 is at or above 100, and 100 is the highest minimum quantity that still fits","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"$2.00 because breaks don't apply to vendor-quoted prices"},{"id":"d","text":"The system averages the two rates"}],"explanation":"For quantity breaks, the system takes the active rate whose minimum quantity is the highest one still at or below what's requested. 250 is at or above 100, so the $1.50 rate wins. If the buyer asked for 50, only the 10-or-more break would qualify and $2.00 would apply."},{"id":"pt8","text":"What does marking a component's source as 'made in-house' do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Marks the component as obsolete"},{"id":"b","text":"Tells the system the component is made in-house, which can spin up a sub-job during production planning","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Locks the component from being edited"},{"id":"d","text":"Hides the component from the tree view"}],"explanation":"A made-in-house component is one you produce yourself. During planning, the system can create a sub-job to build it before the parent job needs it. Bought components trigger purchase orders; from-stock components are assumed to be on hand."},{"id":"pt9","text":"Which tabs does the part detail page show, and how are they chosen?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A fixed five-tab layout — Info, Components, Used In, Routing, Files — the same for every part"},{"id":"b","text":"The tabs are chosen from how you get the part and which bucket it's in. Identity is always first and Files always last (Activity sits as a footer below the tab, not a tab); the tabs in between vary by your choices","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Whatever tabs were last visible — it's a per-user preference"},{"id":"d","text":"Only Identity — every other tab opens in a separate window"}],"explanation":"The page picks its tabs from how you get the part and which bucket it's in. A made finished good might show Identity, Inventory, MRP, Cost, Pricing, Material, Units, Quality, Routing, Components, Sources, Alternates, Purchase History, Activity, and Files. A bought consumable might show only Identity, Inventory, Cost, Pricing, Sources, Activity, and Files. The 3D Viewer tab shows up only when a 3D model is attached."},{"id":"pt10","text":"You delete a part. What happens to its activity log?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It's deleted along with the part"},{"id":"b","text":"It's kept — the part isn't truly deleted, just hidden, and a 'deleted' entry is added","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It's moved to a separate archive"},{"id":"d","text":"It's deleted unless an admin opts to keep it"}],"explanation":"Deletes are soft: the part is hidden from normal views but stays on file, and a 'deleted' entry is logged so a later restore-and-inspect can see exactly what happened. This is true for records across the system."},{"id":"pt11","text":"Where does the New Part flow start?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A long single-page form with every field at once"},{"id":"b","text":"Four quick questions — how you get it, the bucket, an optional item-kind tag, and quick vs guided — that pick a flow and route you into it. Simple cases skip the guided flow and use the one-page quick form","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"You pick a flow from a menu before entering any field"},{"id":"d","text":"There's no choice — every new part uses the same flow"}],"explanation":"New Part starts with those four questions. From your answers the system picks the right flow and walks you through it. You can pause anywhere — your progress is saved as a draft and shown as a faint row on the parts list, ready to resume. Raw materials and consumables go straight to the one-page quick form since they don't need the step-by-step guidance."},{"id":"pt12","text":"Which tab shows the vendors that supply a part — their part numbers, lead times, minimum orders, approved-list status, and quantity-break pricing?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Components"},{"id":"b","text":"Sources","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Cost"},{"id":"d","text":"Material"}],"explanation":"The Sources tab lists every vendor that supplies this part, one row each. It shows the vendor's part number, their manufacturer part number, lead time, minimum order, pack size, country of origin, tariff code, approved-list status, certifications, last-quoted date, preferred marker, and price breaks. The Components tab shows what goes INTO the part; Sources shows where the part comes FROM."},{"id":"pt13","text":"A tool part is bought and used to make other parts. What special link does it support?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It can be linked to a tooling asset to track shot count and maintenance","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"It's added to the Maintenance board automatically"},{"id":"c","text":"It skips inventory tracking entirely"},{"id":"d","text":"It can only be sold, not bought"}],"explanation":"Tool parts can be linked to a tooling asset. The asset tracks current shot count, expected tool life, who owns it (yours or the customer's), and its maintenance schedule — giving you full traceability from the part record back to the physical tool that makes it."},{"id":"pt14","text":"How is a multi-field part update logged?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"One entry per changed field"},{"id":"b","text":"One entry per save, summarizing all the fields you changed (for example, 'Updated 4 fields: name, description, revision, status')","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"No entry — only creates and deletes are logged"},{"id":"d","text":"Two entries: one for the action, one for each field"}],"explanation":"Each save logs one activity entry that summarizes the fields you changed. This keeps the Activity tab readable — the field-by-field record, with old and new values, is what the History tab is for."},{"id":"pt15","text":"You scan a barcode on the Parts page. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A new part is created using the scanned value as its number"},{"id":"b","text":"The scanned value drops into the search box and the list reloads to find the matching part","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The scanned part opens right away"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — scanning only works on the Inventory page"}],"explanation":"On the Parts page, scans feed into search. The scanned value drops into the search box and the list reloads to find the part by its barcode number. From there, click the row to open it."},{"id":"pt16","text":"A part is in Draft. You open it, go to the Identity tab, and click 'Promote to Active'. It has a name and its two choices but no components, and it's a made sub-assembly. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It goes Active right away — Draft is just a label"},{"id":"b","text":"The move is blocked. The readiness checks run, the components check fails, and a panel lists 'BOM not yet defined.' Add a component, then click Promote again","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The status quietly changes to Active but the part stays incomplete"},{"id":"d","text":"You have to delete and recreate the part with components"}],"explanation":"Draft to Active is gated. The Promote to Active button (on the Identity tab, for Draft parts only) runs the readiness checks. A made sub-assembly needs components, so with none the move is blocked and the panel names exactly what's wrong — it never fails silently. Fix the listed items and click Promote again. Finishing the New Part flow runs the same checks and moves the part to Active when they pass."},{"id":"pt17","text":"Which readiness check is required to make a made part Active, but does NOT apply to a bought or subcontracted part?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Routing (at least one manufacturing step)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Sourcing (a preferred vendor picked)"},{"id":"c","text":"Stocking unit (a unit the part is stored in)"},{"id":"d","text":"Basics (a name and the two main choices)"}],"explanation":"Routing needs at least one manufacturing step and only applies to parts you make — bought and subcontracted parts have no in-house steps (the vendor owns the build), so the routing check isn't part of their flow. Conversely, sourcing (a preferred vendor) is required for bought and subcontracted parts but optional for made ones. Which checks apply depends on how you get the part and which bucket it's in."},{"id":"pt18","text":"On a part tracked one-by-one, you open a serial and click 'Genealogy'. What does it show?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The part's list-price history"},{"id":"b","text":"A tree of the serial's parent and child serials — which serialized sub-assemblies were built into this unit, traced down through the build","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Every other serial of the same part, sorted by status"},{"id":"d","text":"The component revision history"}],"explanation":"Genealogy opens a tree of the serial's parents and children — the as-built lineage showing which serialized components went into this unit. It's different from the serial's History (a time-ordered log of its moves) and from the part's component revision history (the planned component list). The Serials tab only appears when the part is tracked one-by-one."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Parts — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "parts-reference",
            Summary = "Deeper reference: the vendor Sources views and price-break history, landed cost versus a manual cost, how material and unit entry works, the Purchase History and 3D Viewer tabs, serial genealogy, and how the New Part flow varies by part.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/parts"]""",
            Tags = """["parts","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Vendor Sources — Views & Price History\n\nThe **Sources** tab shows the same list of vendors three ways, chosen with a view switcher:\n\n- **Inspector** (default) — each vendor collapses to a header, summary, and its price breaks; the vendor's full details (manufacturer part number, lead time, minimum order, pack size, country of origin, tariff code, certifications) show in a panel on the right for whichever vendor you've selected. Best for scanning, then drilling in.\n- **Compare** — vendors stack as cards; expand any card to read its full details inline, side by side with the others.\n- **Pricing** — a flat table across all vendors, one row per price break, sorted so the genuinely cheapest source reads first no matter how each vendor packs the part, then by minimum quantity, then by vendor name. Answers \"where can I buy this at quantity N cheapest?\".\n\n**Price breaks are kept as history, never overwritten.** Changing a break closes the old rate with an end date and adds a new one. The price-breaks panel manages the current set (add or remove); a separate, read-only **price history** view shows every rate, current and closed, newest first — the record of what was quoted or billed before. A **Show history** switch on the Sources tab also dims the closed rates inline in the other views.\n\nWhen the system picks a rate for a quantity break, it only considers rates that are still active on the date — closed rates are history only.\n\n## Landed Cost & Manual Cost\n\nThe **Cost** tab's landed-cost view works out a \"door to door\" average unit cost over your most recent receipts (three by default): a breakdown of the base cost plus freight, duty, and currency effects, the receipts that fed into it, and a vendor comparison so you can spot a cheaper source. When no receipt has captured freight yet, it shows an empty state rather than a misleading number.\n\nLanded cost is calculated, not the cost of record. The **manual cost** is a single price field that, when set, takes over from the calculated cost everywhere downstream (margins, valuation). Clear it to fall back to the calculated value. The calculated cost refreshes on its own whenever a component, vendor, or price changes — and either the calculated cost or a manual one satisfies the Cost readiness check.\n\n## Material & Unit Handling\n\n**Material** measurements let you enter values in whatever unit you prefer, and your unit is kept exactly:\n\n- **Weight** — enter in g, kg, oz, or lb.\n- **Length, width, height** — enter in mm, cm, m, in, or ft.\n- **Volume** — enter in mL, L, oz, or gal.\n\nBehind the scenes the system stores a standard unit and converts back to yours for display, so the value and unit you typed come back unchanged.\n\n**Units** are three separate settings: the **stock** unit (the main inventory unit, and the one the stocking-unit readiness check looks for), the **purchase** unit (which may differ — for example, stock by piece, buy by case), and the **sales** unit. Each vendor's price break also records its own purchase unit and how much is in it, which is how the Pricing view lines every rate up to a comparable per-unit price.\n\n## Purchase History & 3D Viewer Tabs\n\n**Purchase History** is a read-only tab listing the most recent purchase orders that included this part. It has its own search box and shows how many rows it pulled (a count, not an endless history) — a quick \"what have we paid and when\", not a full report.\n\n**3D Viewer** shows up only when a 3D model file is attached to the part (spotted by its filename on the Files list). It renders the model right in the tab. Both the Viewer and Serials tabs are extras added on their own — one when a model is attached, the other when the part is tracked one-by-one — so they appear even when the part's normal tab set wouldn't otherwise include them.\n\n## Serial Genealogy\n\nOn a part tracked one-by-one, opening a serial and clicking **Genealogy** opens a tree of that serial's **parents and children** — the as-built lineage of which serialized sub-assemblies went into this unit, traced down through the build. It's easy to confuse with two neighbors: the serial's **History** (a plain time-ordered log of its moves — the action, where it went from and to, and when) and the part's **component revision history** (the planned component list, not the as-built one). Genealogy answers \"what serialized parts are physically inside this exact unit?\"; revision history answers \"what was this assembly supposed to be made of, and when did that change?\".\n\n## How the New Part Flow Varies\n\nThe four New Part questions pick a flow to fit your answers, and different combinations of how-you-get-it and inventory bucket get different flows. (Phantom parts only come as sub-assemblies or finished goods, never raw materials, components, or consumables.) Each combination declares its own required steps, which is also why the readiness checks differ from one combination to the next.\n\nThe questions also **recommend** a path: simple combinations (like a bought raw material, or a phantom finished good) recommend the one-page quick form, while assembly- or sourcing-heavy combinations (like a made sub-assembly, or a subcontracted component) recommend the guided step-by-step flow. The steps that can appear include basics, inventory, quality, sourcing, vendor and vendor-part details, costing, components, routing, alternates, flags, sales settings, shipping, tool-asset linking, and source part — but each combination only walks the steps it needs (a bought consumable never sees routing; a made finished good does). Today two flows drive the system (an assembly-guided one and a raw-material quick one); more tailored flows are still to come.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Parts training modules");
    }
}
